{"parse":{"title":"Charles W. Sexton","pageid":11262255,"revid":846316005,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">For the British Olympic shooter, see <a href=\"/wiki/Charles_Sexton_(sport_shooter)\" title=\"Charles Sexton (sport shooter)\">Charles Sexton (sport shooter)</a>.</div>\n<table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em;width:25.5em;border-spacing:2px;\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;background-color:#C3D6EF;\"><span class=\"fn\">Charles Sexton</span></th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;border-bottom: 1px solid #aaa;; line-height: 1.5em\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Petty_Officer_Charles_Sexton_lost_his_life_helping_to_save_fishermen_off_the_Oregon_coast.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Petty Officer Charles Sexton lost his life helping to save fishermen off the Oregon coast.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fe/Petty_Officer_Charles_Sexton_lost_his_life_helping_to_save_fishermen_off_the_Oregon_coast.jpg/160px-Petty_Officer_Charles_Sexton_lost_his_life_helping_to_save_fishermen_off_the_Oregon_coast.jpg\" width=\"160\" height=\"220\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fe/Petty_Officer_Charles_Sexton_lost_his_life_helping_to_save_fishermen_off_the_Oregon_coast.jpg/240px-Petty_Officer_Charles_Sexton_lost_his_life_helping_to_save_fishermen_off_the_Oregon_coast.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fe/Petty_Officer_Charles_Sexton_lost_his_life_helping_to_save_fishermen_off_the_Oregon_coast.jpg/320px-Petty_Officer_Charles_Sexton_lost_his_life_helping_to_save_fishermen_off_the_Oregon_coast.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"489\" data-file-height=\"673\" /></a><div style=\"font-size: 100%\">Petty Officer Charles Sexton lost his life helping to save fishermen off the Oregon coast.</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right: 1em\">Service/<wbr />branch</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Coast_Guard\" title=\"United States Coast Guard\">United States Coast Guard</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Charles W. Sexton</b>, Machinery Technician First Class, <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Coast_Guard\" title=\"United States Coast Guard\">USCG</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> was awarded a posthumous award of the <a href=\"/wiki/Coast_Guard_Medal\" title=\"Coast Guard Medal\">Coast Guard Medal</a> for \"extraordinary heroism.\"\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Action_cited\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Action cited</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Coast_Guard_Medal_citation\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Coast Guard Medal citation</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Sexton_Hall\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Sexton Hall</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Cape_Disappointment\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Cape Disappointment</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#USCGC_Charles_Sexton\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">USCGC <i>Charles Sexton</i></span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-8\"><a href=\"#Sources\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">8</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Sources</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Action_cited\">Action cited</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Charles_W._Sexton&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Action cited\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Sexton died during the rescue of fishermen stranded off the treacherous <a href=\"/wiki/Columbia_River\" title=\"Columbia River\">Columbia River</a> bar.<sup id=\"cite_ref-UscgBioCharlesSexton_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-UscgBioCharlesSexton-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-UscgHeroes2010-10-17_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-UscgHeroes2010-10-17-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-WhoAreHeroes_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-WhoAreHeroes-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>A Coast Guard Motor Lifeboat Crew had proceeded to the <a href=\"/wiki/Fishing_trawler\" title=\"Fishing trawler\">fishing trawler</a> <i>Sea King</i> in <i>motor lifeboat 44381</i>, because the trawler had lost power off the Columbia bar, and was taking on water. Sexton had helped treat a wounded fisherman, had helped bring over portable pumps to pump out the trawler, when the trawler unexpectedly turned over. Two of the trawler's crew, and the Coast Guardsmen, were thrown into the Ocean, and were eventually rescued, but Sexton and two other crew members were trapped in the vessel's pilot house, and drowned.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Coast_Guard_Medal_citation\">Coast Guard Medal citation</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Charles_W._Sexton&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Coast Guard Medal citation\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>His award citation stated: \n</p>\n<blockquote><p>Petty Officer SEXTON is cited for extraordinary heroism on 11 January 1991 while serving as <a href=\"/wiki/Emergency_medical_technician\" title=\"Emergency medical technician\">emergency medical technician</a> aboard <a href=\"/wiki/USCG_motor_life_boat\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"USCG motor life boat\">Coast Guard Motor Lifeboat</a> CG-44381. The boat crew was responding to a distress call from F/V SEA KING, a 75-foot stern <a href=\"/wiki/Fishing_trawler\" title=\"Fishing trawler\">trawler</a> with four persons on board, which was taking on water and in danger of sinking, four nautical miles northwest of the <a href=\"/wiki/Columbia_River_Bar\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Columbia River Bar\">Columbia River Bar</a>, with her decks awash and after compartment and engine room steadily filling up with water. From the relative safety the motor lifeboat, Petty Officer SEXTON unselfishly volunteered to go aboard the foundering fishing vessel to treat the injuries of a SEA KING crew member who had fallen to the deck boat during a failed helicopter hoist. He skillfully diagnosed the victim\u2019s injuries, informed the flight surgeon of the extent of the injuries and provided first aid treatment. Once the victim was stabilized, Petty Officer SEXTON turned his attention to assisting with the dewatering of the vessel. The SEA KING required several dewatering pumps to remove the initial quantity of sea water from the engine room. Then, hourly dewatering of the vessel was necessary to maintain proper trim aboard the vessel. After more than 6 hours of this exhausting routine, with the worst of the treacherous bar crossing behind them, the SEA KING suddenly, without warning, rolled over, throwing victims into the churning seas and trapping Petty Officer SEXTON in the enclosed pilot house. He went down with vessel, sacrificing his life while attempting to save the lives of the SEA KING\u2019s crew members. Petty Officer SEXTON demonstrated remarkable initiative, exceptional fortitude, and daring in spite of imminent danger in this rescue. His courage and devotion to duty are most heartily commended and are in keeping with the highest traditions of the United States Coast Guard.\n</p></blockquote>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sexton_Hall\">Sexton Hall</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Charles_W._Sexton&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Sexton Hall\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The first barracks new Coast Guard recruits stay at, upon their arrival at the Coast Guard training depot in <a href=\"/wiki/Cape_May,_New_Jersey\" title=\"Cape May, New Jersey\">Cape May, New Jersey</a>, is named <i>\"Sexton Hall\"</i>, in his honor.\n<sup id=\"cite_ref-ChinookObserver_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ChinookObserver-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Recruits stay there during their orientation, prior to their assignment to a training unit.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Upon arriving to recruit basic training in <a href=\"/wiki/Cape_May,_New_Jersey\" title=\"Cape May, New Jersey\">Cape May, New Jersey</a>, recruits spend their first three nights in <i>Sexton Hall</i> for forming, and before being put into a company.  Named after Charles W. Sexton, there are tributes to him within the barracks.Sexton Hall is also the residence of recruits discharged before completion of recruit training awaiting orders home (whether for medical or disciplinary reasons).\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Cape_Disappointment\">Cape Disappointment</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Charles_W._Sexton&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Cape Disappointment\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The Coast Guard's National Motor Lifeboat School where Sexton was stationed at the time of his death, named the maintenance building in his honor.<sup id=\"cite_ref-ChinookObserver_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ChinookObserver-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-ChinookLetter_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ChinookLetter-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> A bronze relief plaque is displayed at the building entrance to remind staff and students of his ultimate sacrifice.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"USCGC_Charles_Sexton\">USCGC <i>Charles Sexton</i></span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Charles_W._Sexton&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: USCGC Charles Sexton\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"floatleft\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Newly_delivered_USCGC_Charles_Sexton,_underway.jpg\" class=\"image\" title=\"USCGC Charles Sexton\"><img alt=\"USCGC Charles Sexton\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Newly_delivered_USCGC_Charles_Sexton%2C_underway.jpg/260px-Newly_delivered_USCGC_Charles_Sexton%2C_underway.jpg\" width=\"260\" height=\"195\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Newly_delivered_USCGC_Charles_Sexton%2C_underway.jpg/390px-Newly_delivered_USCGC_Charles_Sexton%2C_underway.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Newly_delivered_USCGC_Charles_Sexton%2C_underway.jpg/520px-Newly_delivered_USCGC_Charles_Sexton%2C_underway.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"700\" data-file-height=\"525\" /></a></div>\n<p>In 2010, when the Coast Guard decided that all the new <a href=\"/wiki/Sentinel_class_cutters\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sentinel class cutters\">Sentinel class cutters</a> would be named after Coast Guard personnel who had been recognized for their heroism, Sexton was one of those to be honored.<sup id=\"cite_ref-UscgHeroes2010-10-17_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-UscgHeroes2010-10-17-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Daily2014-04-01_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Daily2014-04-01-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\nThe 8th cutter in the class will be named the <a href=\"/wiki/USCGC_Charles_Sexton_(WPC_1108)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"USCGC Charles Sexton (WPC 1108)\">USCGC <i>Charles Sexton</i></a>.  She will be homeported in <a href=\"/wiki/Key_West,_Florida\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Key West, Florida\">Key West, Florida</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-DefenseMediaNetwork2012-11-05_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DefenseMediaNetwork2012-11-05-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>A 154' USCG <a href=\"/wiki/Sentinel_class_cutter\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sentinel class cutter\">Sentinel-Class Fast Response Cutter</a> that bears his name was commissioned in Key West, FL on March 8, 2014.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Charles_W._Sexton&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/USCGC_Charles_Sexton_(WPC-1108)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"USCGC Charles Sexton (WPC-1108)\">USCGC Charles Sexton (WPC-1108)</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Charles_W._Sexton&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://coastguard.dodlive.mil/2010/11/coast-guard-heroes-charles-sexton/\">\"Machinery Technician First Class Charles W. Sexton\"</a>, USCG\"</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-UscgBioCharlesSexton-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-UscgBioCharlesSexton_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite class=\"citation news\">Connie Braesch (2010-11-04). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://coastguard.dodlive.mil/index.php/2010/11/coast-guard-heroes-charles-sexton/\">\"Coast Guard Heroes: Charles Walter David Jr\"</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Coast_Guard\" title=\"United States Coast Guard\">United States Coast Guard</a>. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fcoastguard.dodlive.mil%2Findex.php%2F2010%2F11%2Fcoast-guard-heroes-charles-sexton%2F&amp;date=2013-01-04\">Archived</a> from the original on 2013-01-04. <q>Many of the Coast Guard\u2019s heroes fought in wars abroad or found themselves under enemy fire in foreign countries. But, Charles W. Sexton found himself faced with danger in the course of his everyday duties at Coast Guard Station Cape Disappointment. Sexton, a machinery technician, was rescuing four fishermen in peril when the seas tragically took him.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Coast+Guard+Heroes%3A+Charles+Walter+David+Jr.&amp;rft.date=2010-11-04&amp;rft.au=Connie+Braesch&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fcoastguard.dodlive.mil%2Findex.php%2F2010%2F11%2Fcoast-guard-heroes-charles-sexton%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACharles+W.+Sexton\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-UscgHeroes2010-10-17-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-UscgHeroes2010-10-17_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-UscgHeroes2010-10-17_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite class=\"citation news\">Stephanie Young (2010-10-27). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fcoastguard.dodlive.mil%2F2010%2F10%2Fcoast-guard-heroes%2F&amp;date=2013-01-03\">\"Coast Guard Heroes\"</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Coast_Guard\" title=\"United States Coast Guard\">United States Coast Guard</a>. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://coastguard.dodlive.mil/2010/10/coast-guard-heroes/\">the original</a> on 2013-01-03<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2012-04-20</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Coast+Guard+Heroes&amp;rft.date=2010-10-27&amp;rft.au=Stephanie+Young&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fcoastguard.dodlive.mil%2F2010%2F10%2Fcoast-guard-heroes%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACharles+W.+Sexton\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-WhoAreHeroes-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-WhoAreHeroes_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.uscg.mil%2Fhistory%2Ffaqs%2Fvip.asp&amp;date=2014-08-27\">\"Who are some of the heroes of the Coast Guard?\"</a>. USCG. 2012-12-03. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.uscg.mil/history/faqs/vip.asp\">the original</a> on 2014-08-27<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2013-01-10</span></span>. <q>His award citation stated: \"Petty Officer SEXTON is cited for extraordinary heroism on 11 January 1991 while serving as emergency medical technician aboard Coast Guard Motor Lifeboat CG-44381.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Who+are+some+of+the+heroes+of+the+Coast+Guard%3F&amp;rft.date=2012-12-03&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.uscg.mil%2Fhistory%2Ffaqs%2Fvip.asp&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACharles+W.+Sexton\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span>  </span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-ChinookObserver-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-ChinookObserver_5-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-ChinookObserver_5-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite class=\"citation news\">Kevin Heimberger (2012-04-10). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.chinookobserver.com/news/new-uscg-cutter-to-be-named-after-sexton/article_6d33307e-8377-11e1-b6a4-0019bb2963f4.html\">\"New USCG cutter to be named after Sexton\"</a>. Chinook Observer. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.chinookobserver.com%2Fnews%2Fnew-uscg-cutter-to-be-named-after-sexton%2Farticle_6d33307e-8377-11e1-b6a4-0019bb2963f4.html&amp;date=2014-03-15\">Archived</a> from the original on 2014-03-15<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2014-03-15</span></span>. <q>Upon arriving to basic training in Cape May, N.J., all USCG recruits spend their first three nights in Sexton Hall for forming, and before being put into a company. Sexton Hall is also the residence of Coast Guardsmen awaiting orders to go home.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=New+USCG+cutter+to+be+named+after+Sexton&amp;rft.date=2012-04-10&amp;rft.au=Kevin+Heimberger&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.chinookobserver.com%2Fnews%2Fnew-uscg-cutter-to-be-named-after-sexton%2Farticle_6d33307e-8377-11e1-b6a4-0019bb2963f4.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACharles+W.+Sexton\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite class=\"citation book\">David Helvarg (2009). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=NQj0EVuzVTEC&amp;pg=PA33&amp;lpg=PA33&amp;dq=USCG+OR+%22Coast+Guard%22+%22Sexton+Hall%22&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=Nn1MGjKPzI&amp;sig=L8_tleCjnhijPhe0PZM6gtoUWrw&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=y6IkU-9P0tqpAcvjgcAH&amp;redir_esc=y#v=onepage&amp;q=USCG%20OR%20%22Coast%20Guard%22%20%22Sexton%20Hall%22&amp;f=false\"><i>Rescue Warriors: The U.S. Coast Guard, America's Forgotten Heroes</i></a>. <a href=\"/wiki/Macmillan_Books\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Macmillan Books\">Macmillan Books</a>. p.&#160;33. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781429989534\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9781429989534\">9781429989534</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2014-03-15</span></span>. <q>The morning after their arrival, the fifty-six new recruits are marched onto the second floor of Sexton Hall, named for Charles Sexton, a Coastie medic who died after trying to administer first aid aboard the fishing vessel <i>Sea King</i> when it capsized and sank new the mouth of the Columbia River in 1991.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Rescue+Warriors%3A+The+U.S.+Coast+Guard%2C+America%27s+Forgotten+Heroes&amp;rft.pages=33&amp;rft.pub=Macmillan+Books&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.isbn=9781429989534&amp;rft.au=David+Helvarg&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DNQj0EVuzVTEC%26pg%3DPA33%26lpg%3DPA33%26dq%3DUSCG%2BOR%2B%2522Coast%2BGuard%2522%2B%2522Sexton%2BHall%2522%26source%3Dbl%26ots%3DNn1MGjKPzI%26sig%3DL8_tleCjnhijPhe0PZM6gtoUWrw%26hl%3Den%26sa%3DX%26ei%3Dy6IkU-9P0tqpAcvjgcAH%26redir_esc%3Dy%23v%3Donepage%26q%3DUSCG%2520OR%2520%2522Coast%2520Guard%2522%2520%2522Sexton%2520Hall%2522%26f%3Dfalse&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACharles+W.+Sexton\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-ChinookLetter-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-ChinookLetter_7-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite class=\"citation news\">James B. Taylor (2012-11-20). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.northwestopinions.com/chinook-observer/letter-will-always-honor-sexton/\">\"Letter: Will always honor Sexton\"</a>. Chinook Observer. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20140315200331/http://www.northwestopinions.com/chinook-observer/letter-will-always-honor-sexton/\">Archived</a> from the original on 2014-03-15<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2014-03-15</span></span>. <q>I was stationed with Petty Officer Sexton at the National Motor Lifeboat School in Ilwaco. He was my supervisor. I was a fireman apprentice at the time and I was there the evening he passed away. He allowed us to call him Rudy, and he was a great guy. As my career continued after his passing, and when the seas seemed too rough to handle, I would try and think how he would have handled the situation.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Letter%3A+Will+always+honor+Sexton&amp;rft.date=2012-11-20&amp;rft.au=James+B.+Taylor&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.northwestopinions.com%2Fchinook-observer%2Fletter-will-always-honor-sexton%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACharles+W.+Sexton\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Daily2014-04-01-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Daily2014-04-01_8-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/voted-off-the-island-the-uscgs-deepwater-frc-program-03160/\">\"FRC Plan B: The Sentinel Class\"</a>. <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Defense_Industry_Daily&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Defense Industry Daily (page does not exist)\">Defense Industry Daily</a>. 2014-05-02. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20140707003537/http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/voted-off-the-island-the-uscgs-deepwater-frc-program-03160/\">Archived</a> from the original on 2014-07-07<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2014-04-03</span></span>. <q>All of these boats will be named after enlisted Coast Guard heroes, who distinguished themselves in USCG or military service. The first 25 have been named, but only 8 have been commissioned...</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=FRC+Plan+B%3A+The+Sentinel+Class&amp;rft.date=2014-05-02&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.defenseindustrydaily.com%2Fvoted-off-the-island-the-uscgs-deepwater-frc-program-03160%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACharles+W.+Sexton\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-DefenseMediaNetwork2012-11-05-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-DefenseMediaNetwork2012-11-05_9-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite class=\"citation news\">Rhonda Carpenter (2012-11-05). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.defensemedianetwork.com/stories/coast-guard-commissions-third-fast-response-cutter-william-flores/\">\"Coast Guard Commissions Third Fast Response Cutter, William Flores\"</a>. Defense Media Network. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.defensemedianetwork.com%2Fstories%2Fcoast-guard-commissions-third-fast-response-cutter-william-flores%2F&amp;date=2013-01-04\">Archived</a> from the original on 2013-01-04. <q>The first six FRCs for District 7 will be homeported in Miami; the next six in Key West; and the remaining six in Puerto Rico.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Coast+Guard+Commissions+Third+Fast+Response+Cutter%2C+William+Flores&amp;rft.date=2012-11-05&amp;rft.au=Rhonda+Carpenter&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.defensemedianetwork.com%2Fstories%2Fcoast-guard-commissions-third-fast-response-cutter-william-flores%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACharles+W.+Sexton\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sources\">Sources</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Charles_W._Sexton&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8\" title=\"Edit section: Sources\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.webcitation.org/6S9dySdGs?url=http://www.uscg.mil/history/faqs/vip.asp\">are some of the heroes of the Coast Guard?\", USCG</a></li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2232\nCached time: 20180921225101\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.196 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.256 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count